● What is the Residential vs. other property type share?
Residential is the dominant property type, making up 67% of sold transactions and 63% of listings. ResidentialLease is
the second largest at 23% of sold and 21% of listings. All other types (Land, ManufacturedInPark, CommercialSale, etc.)
each make up less than 4%.

● What are the median and average close prices?
The median close price is $820,000 and the mean is $1,185,616. The large gap between the two indicates strong right
skew, a relatively small number of very high-priced sales are pulling the average up significantly.

● What does the Days on Market distribution look like?
The median DOM is 19 days and the mean is 37, again showing right skew. 75% of homes sell within 48 days, but the 95th
percentile is 131 days and the max is 12,430 which is clearly a data quality issue worth flagging. There are also
negative DOM values (min of -288) which are invalid and will need to be cleaned.

● What percentage of homes sold above vs. below list price?
40.1% of homes sold above list price and 59.9% sold below, suggesting the market slightly favors buyers overall, though
a significant portion of sellers are still getting over asking.

● Are there any apparent date consistency issues (e.g., close date before listing date)?
58 records have a CloseDate before their ListingContractDate, which is logically impossible and flags a data quality
issue to address in the cleaning phase.

● Which counties have the highest median prices?
San Mateo ($1.7M), Santa Clara ($1.6M), and Santa Cruz ($1.2M) are the top legitimate counties. Del Norte ($2.49M) and
"Other County" ($2.46M) rank highest but likely reflect data quality issues given their small sample sizes and unusual
values.